{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7fc3ddd2-437f-4e1c-8959-68be4f293e0f","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. From inside the container:\n\n```bash\n# Install the tool (if not already present)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to **speedscope** format:\n\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips for K8s specifically:**\n\n- If the SDK isn't in the container, copy the tool in via `kubectl cp` or use a sidecar/ephemeral debug container.\n- For a lower-overhead alternative, use **`dotnet-counters`** first to confirm CPU is actually in managed code (`System.Runtime cpu-usage`).\n- If CPU is in native code, use **`perf`** instead (`perf record -g -p <PID>`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a2d9fa32-f5bc-4a25-97e4-c01670019167","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task. I'll provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":332,"requestId":"AC0B:271D55:13A4C5D:16149BD:6A067110"},"id":"aab5880c-2dcb-42fa-b9d3-3216ec723848","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:04:25.246Z","parentId":"204f8ced-8158-4f7c-a48b-a0e648ea2ec7"}
